  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, creating spaces for roosting bats in road bridges showed mixed success with recolonization occurring at four of eight sites in similar or greater numbers to the original roosts (Action 1967). When maintaining existing bat roosts during road bridge repair work, results were species-specific: a maternity colony of Daubenton's bats continued to roost in similar numbers after crevices were retained, and Yuma myotis and Mexican free-tailed bats recolonised most roosts in similar numbers, but pallid bats did not return (Action 1966). The key limitation identified was that alternative bat roosts provided during bridge replacement works were significantly less effective, with bat houses being used by fewer Mexican free-tailed bats than the original roost at one site and not used at all at three sites (Action 2942). All documented studies were based on research in the USA and one study in Ireland, indicating limited geographic coverage of evidence for these conservation approaches.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1967",
    "1966",
    "2942"
  ]
}

