  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for managing existing hedgerows for bats significantly outweighs the evidence for planting new hedges. Two studies in the UK evaluated the effects of managing hedges to benefit bat populations (Action 1943). These studies found that hedges trimmed three or more years prior had more bat species recorded along them than hedges trimmed during the previous winter, and had higher activity of two of eight bat species/species groups than recently trimmed hedges. One study found that pipistrelle activity did not differ between hedges managed for wildlife on agri-environment scheme farms and hedges on conventional farms. In contrast, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of planting new hedges on bat populations (Action 1942).",
