{
  "query": "How does the evidence for legally protecting bat habitats compare to legally protecting bats during development activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for legally protecting bat habitats is substantially more comprehensive than for legally protecting bats during development activities. For habitat protection (action 2045), five studies evaluated effects on bat populations across Europe and India, showing mixed but generally positive results including higher bat activity in protected areas, greater species numbers in some protected sites, and significant overlap between bat distributions and designated protection areas. In contrast, evidence for legal protection during development (action 1935) comes from only four studies, all conducted in the UK, with no studies measuring community or population responses. The development protection studies focused primarily on behavioral changes and impacts on roost sites, finding that 68% of roosts were destroyed during licensed activities and only 31-67% of compensation roosts were actually used by bats. Additionally, 81% of licensees failed to conduct post-development monitoring. The habitat protection evidence demonstrates measurable ecological benefits, while development protection evidence reveals implementation challenges and limited effectiveness of compensation measures.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2045",
    "1935"
  ]
}

