{"query": "What conservation actions can be implemented to combat the spread and impact of white-nose syndrome in bats?", "summary": "Several conservation actions have been identified specifically for combating white-nose syndrome in bats, though many lack scientific evaluation. Direct treatment approaches include treating bats with probiotic bacteria, where two studies found that treating little brown bats with probiotic bacterium at the time of infection increased survival in laboratory settings and for free-flying bats in mines, and reduced disease symptoms when applied at infection time (action 2008). However, treatment 21 days prior to infection worsened symptoms. 

Prevention and containment measures include restricting human access to bat caves to reduce pathogen spread (action 1010), decontaminating clothing and equipment after entering caves (action 2006), treating hibernacula environments to reduce pathogen reservoirs (action 2007), and culling infected bats (action 1012). Vaccination against the white-nose syndrome pathogen has been proposed (action 1011). Population supplementation through captive breeding programs specifically for white-nose syndrome affected populations has been considered (action 2009).

Most of these actions have not yet been scientifically evaluated for effectiveness, with studies available only for probiotic treatment approaches. The available evidence suggests that timing of probiotic treatment is critical for effectiveness.", "action_ids": ["1012","1011","2008","2009","1010","2007","2006"]}

